<div id="review_571046088" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/571046088" />
    <a title="Scott" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/445677-scott"><img alt="Scott" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1487280374p2/445677.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/571046088?book_show_action=true">Mar 25, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Scott" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Scott" href="/user/show/445677-scott">Scott</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer571046088" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1481950170017802919">This is the second book I have read by Alberto Manguel. The first, &quot;The Library at Night,&quot; was magnificent, and it left me eager to enjoy more of his erudite prose and wide-ranging stories of scholars and enthusiasts within the literary and humanist tradition. In &quot;A History of Reading&quot; the chapters cover eclectic topics, providing not a chronological but a conceptual history of reading and supporting stories of readers. I found myself wanting to spend time ruminating on each chapter, so I found </span>
  <span id="freeText1481950170017802919" style="display:none">This is the second book I have read by Alberto Manguel. The first, "The Library at Night," was magnificent, and it left me eager to enjoy more of his erudite prose and wide-ranging stories of scholars and enthusiasts within the literary and humanist tradition. In "A History of Reading" the chapters cover eclectic topics, providing not a chronological but a conceptual history of reading and supporting stories of readers. I found myself wanting to spend time ruminating on each chapter, so I found myself not eager to rush, but rather to contemplate and think more deeply. For me the history of reading, and of the developments from the scroll to the codex to the hypertext, parallel and synapse with the history of ideas of knowledge, of society, of the religious, humanist, and scientific enterprises - in short, for me to be a reader is fundamental to being fully human, and I intend this thought broadly and in a non-elitist context. We understand ourselves through what we read. For me this book continued and extended this dialogue in a most pleasant manner.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1481950170017802919" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


