<div id="review_2868821386" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2868821386" />
    <a title="Revanth Ukkalam" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/35973717-revanth-ukkalam"><img alt="Revanth Ukkalam" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1524328007p2/35973717.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2868821386?book_show_action=true">Jun 25, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Revanth Ukkalam" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Revanth Ukkalam" href="/user/show/35973717-revanth-ukkalam">Revanth Ukkalam</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/35973717-revanth-ukkalam?shelf=postmodernism">postmodernism</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/35973717-revanth-ukkalam?shelf=cultural-history">cultural-history</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2868821386" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12870228150954046657">The author of a &apos;Night at the library&apos; is a reader. To him reading seems to be an essential facet of life - only he does it not to survive but live. This shows in his history of reading. He offers nuggets from history and the worlds of texts and reading to illuminate particular elements of reading - like reading quiet, reading alone, judging a person by the book&apos;s cover, and forbidden reading. As if that were not enough he tops it with anecdotes; of growing up with books and even more fantastic,</span>
  <span id="freeText12870228150954046657" style="display:none">The author of a 'Night at the library' is a reader. To him reading seems to be an essential facet of life - only he does it not to survive but live. This shows in his history of reading. He offers nuggets from history and the worlds of texts and reading to illuminate particular elements of reading - like reading quiet, reading alone, judging a person by the book's cover, and forbidden reading. As if that were not enough he tops it with anecdotes; of growing up with books and even more fantastic, with Borges. He answers questions that are not profound but fun to think about but ignored (because of their mundaneness). Finally the book is not even a history in the usual sense of the word. There is no chronology but there are ideas and lots and lots of words.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12870228150954046657" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
