<div id="review_307111147" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/307111147" />
    <a title="1.1" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3728503-1-1"><img alt="1.1" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1307338551p2/3728503.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/307111147?book_show_action=true">Apr 05, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="1.1" class="user" itemprop="url" name="1.1" href="/user/show/3728503-1-1">1.1</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer307111147" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15775471413712161465">I am guilty lately of overusing the term &apos;interesting&apos; to refer to books in quick, discouraged reviews. Clearly I&apos;ve not been passionate enough about reviewing properly. I sincerely doubt things will change unless I get back in the habit of keeping notes and page numbers for quotes and all that work business, which I feel detract from the pleasures of reading.<br/><br/>Alberto Manguel does pretty much what an enshrined member of the establishment would do: a learned summary of reading, in purple prose, wi</span>
  <span id="freeText15775471413712161465" style="display:none">I am guilty lately of overusing the term 'interesting' to refer to books in quick, discouraged reviews. Clearly I've not been passionate enough about reviewing properly. I sincerely doubt things will change unless I get back in the habit of keeping notes and page numbers for quotes and all that work business, which I feel detract from the pleasures of reading.<br /><br />Alberto Manguel does pretty much what an enshrined member of the establishment would do: a learned summary of reading, in purple prose, with very interesting anecdotes. He also glosses over the negative aspects of reading: the tracts and ideological messes, the elitism, the mountains of paper wasted on trivial hacks, dangerous idiots, and dull nonsense. The people permanently crippled by print are mostly ignored, too.<br /><br />But Alberto had a cool, dangerous, sickly and cloistered life. He doesn't even pause to tell us what gender his lover was – ah but of course, the book is 'a' history, and not his history of reading. If only he stuck to that course a little more often. Still, he brings his own experiences into the book often, and mostly they add zest to the pages, but for all that the title remains slightly deceptive.<br /><br />Definitely worth reading. It can be a quick, casual read, and is not entirely lacking in rigor.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15775471413712161465" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


