    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3548642528" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3548642528" />
    <a title="Andrew" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/769356-andrew"><img alt="Andrew" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1479423940p2/769356.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3548642528?book_show_action=true">Sep 14, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Andrew" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Andrew" href="/user/show/769356-andrew">Andrew</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3548642528" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7741039688025061433">Widely read, widely traveled, Alberto Manguel offers a series of brief historical essays on various aspects of reading from around the world over the last six millennia. <br/><br/>Every chapter contains stimulating tidbits. We read of the creative but (to us) farfetched theories the ancients had on how people were actually able to decipher markings on a stone or piece of papyrus. One of the world’s most notorious rare book thieves, we learn, was Count Guglielmo Libri who permanently checked out hundreds o</span>
  <span id="freeText7741039688025061433" style="display:none">Widely read, widely traveled, Alberto Manguel offers a series of brief historical essays on various aspects of reading from around the world over the last six millennia. <br /><br />Every chapter contains stimulating tidbits. We read of the creative but (to us) farfetched theories the ancients had on how people were actually able to decipher markings on a stone or piece of papyrus. One of the world’s most notorious rare book thieves, we learn, was Count Guglielmo Libri who permanently checked out hundreds of items from special library collections throughout Europe in the nineteen century. <br /><br />Aristocratic women in medieval Japan were forced to develop their own literature since they were so severely cut off from the world. In the first century AD Roman Pliny the Younger found reason to castigate and praise authors who read (the better ones would perform) their latest creations to a gathering of friends and others. <br /> <br />I knew of the ways monks would read the Bible: lectio, meditatio, oratio and contemplation. Manguel notes that the Ashkenazi Talmudic scholars also used a different set of four simultaneous levels of reading -- the “<i>Pshat</i> or literal sense, <i>Remez</i> or limited meeting, <i>Drash</i> or rational elaboration and <i>Sod</i> or occult, secret, mystical meaning” (p. 90).<br /><br />The author also intermixes some of his own experiences into the book. When Manguel told about how he read, while a teenager, to the blind Jorge Luis Borges for several years, I found myself in a rare state of jealousy. How fascinating to have been able to hear Borges’s comments on Kipling, Keats, Milton, Joyce, Estrada, Papini, Lovecraft, Waugh, and more! Understandably, Manguel describes this task as a “happy captivity," as is this book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7741039688025061433" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


